---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
const commercialBody = `

  <header class="hero hero--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="hero-grid">
        <div class="hero-text">
          <div class="hero-eyebrow eyebrow">Creative Earners &middot; Commercial Talent</div>
          <h1 class="display-1">Mortgages for Commercial Talent</h1>
          <p class="lead hero-subtitle">Mortgages for Florida commercial talent &mdash; on-camera commercial principals, voiceover artists, print talent, digital + social media talent, and industrial + corporate + medical narration talent &mdash; qualifying on session fees + residuals + buyouts + holding fees with multi-source W-2 + S-corp loan-out K-1 + 1099 synthesis. Florida commercial talent operate within the <a href="https://www.sagaftra.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline;">SAG-AFTRA (Screen Actors Guild-American Federation of Television and Radio Artists)</a> framework under the <a href="https://www.sagaftra.org/contracts-industry-resources/contracts/commercials-contract" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline;">SAG-AFTRA Commercials Contract</a> negotiated with the Joint Policy Committee (JPC) representing the <a href="https://www.ana.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline;">ANA (Association of National Advertisers)</a> + <a href="https://www.aaaa.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline;">4As (American Association of Advertising Agencies)</a>, separate from the TV/Theatrical contract that governs scripted episodic + features. Following the 2023 SAG-AFTRA TV/Theatrical strike (July-November 2023) parallel to the WGA strike, the resulting contract included AI protections (digital replica consent + compensation) + streaming residual improvements + viewership metric transparency. Commercial talent compensation combines session fees (paid for the actual work day), residuals (paid for re-use across networks + cable + web + social), buyouts (lump-sum payment substituting for residuals common for digital/social/non-broadcast media), holding fees (paid to keep talent available between sessions for conflict purposes), and <a href="https://www.sagaftraplans.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline;">SAG-AFTRA Health Plan + Pension</a> contributions from signatory employers. <strong>Florida commercial talent practice spans five primary categories: on-camera commercial principal as lead/featured performer in TV + streaming + theatrical commercials with session fee $711+ per day (current SAG-AFTRA Commercials Contract Class A rate) + substantial residuals on network + cable + web + foreign + holding fees, total $60K-$350K+ depending on booking frequency + commercial tier; voiceover artist for commercial VO + animation + ADR (Automated Dialog Replacement) + audiobook + e-learning + corporate narration with session fees $466+ per session (1-hour SAG-AFTRA standard) + residuals + buyouts, top-tier VO talent on recurring national campaigns $200K-$500K+; print + still photography talent with one-time fee + use period structure (no traditional residuals; usage-based compensation), $35K-$150K typical range; digital + social media talent for web + social + streaming + influencer-adjacent commercial work, frequently buyout-based for streaming platforms + social media + sometimes non-union, $50K-$250K range depending on platform + reach; industrial + corporate + medical narration talent for internal corporate training + medical narration + e-learning + product demos, frequently non-union or SAG-AFTRA Industrial agreement, $45K-$150K typical range.</strong> For mortgage qualifying, multi-source commercial talent income synthesizes under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline;">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a> for W-2 session fees + residuals with 24-month averaging, <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.5-01/underwriting-factors-and-documentation-self-employed-borrower" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline;">B3-3.2-01</a> for 1099 non-union work + corporate + e-learning, and <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.7-01/analyzing-partnership-returns-partnership-or-llc" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline;">B3-3.4-02</a> for loan-out S-corp K-1. Bank Statement Non-QM + Asset-Depletion Non-QM common alternative paths for lumpy booking-based income. <strong>Stairway Mortgage routinely handles Florida commercial talent mortgages with multi-source synthesis + loan-out S-corp + residuals/buyouts + booking variability smoothing + Florida bilingual commercial market context.</strong></p>
          <div class="hero-actions">
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call" class="btn btn-primary btn-large">Schedule a call with Jim</a>
            <a href="#commercial-roles" class="btn btn-secondary btn-large">See commercial talent roles</a>
          </div>
          <div class="hero-trust">
            <span class="trust-dot"></span><span>Broker NMLS #1072866</span><span>&middot;</span>
            <span>FL mortgage broker specializing in commercial talent multi-source: SAG-AFTRA W-2 session fees + residuals + buyouts + S-corp loan-out K-1 + 1099 corporate + bilingual market</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="hero-image"><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/2773498/pexels-photo-2773498.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1200" alt="Florida commercial talent SAG-AFTRA on-camera voiceover performer" width="1200" height="1500" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1200x1500/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=Commercial+Talent';"></figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="stats stats--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="stats-bar-grid">
        <div class="stats-grid">
          <div class="stat"><div class="stat-num">$35K-$500K+ income</div><div class="stat-label">SAG-AFTRA commercial talent income $35K (entry print) to $500K+ (top-tier VO national campaigns). Multi-source W-2 session fees + residuals + buyouts + holding fees + S-corp loan-out K-1 + 1099 non-union. <a href="https://www.sagaftra.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: inherit;">SAG-AFTRA</a> 160,000+ members</div></div>
          <div class="stat"><div class="stat-num">Session + residuals + buyouts</div><div class="stat-label">Commercial compensation = session fees (paid for work day) + residuals (re-use across networks + cable + web + foreign) + buyouts (lump-sum substituting for residuals) + holding fees (keeping talent available between sessions for conflicts)</div></div>
          <div class="stat"><div class="stat-num">Loan-out S-corp standard</div><div class="stat-label">Loan-out company S-corp PLLC standard for established commercial talent. Agency contracts loan-out; loan-out pays W-2 wages + S-corp K-1 to talent. Multi-entity Form 1084 cash-flow analysis required for mortgage qualifying</div></div>
          <div class="stat"><div class="stat-num">FL bilingual commercial market</div><div class="stat-label">Miami substantial Spanish-language commercial production market (Univision, Telemundo, ViX, ViX+) targeting US Hispanic market. Bilingual commercial talent substantial career opportunity. South Florida + Orlando substantial commercial production base</div></div>
        </div>
        <figure class="stats-bar-image"><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/3771088/pexels-photo-3771088.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1000" alt="Florida commercial talent voiceover studio" width="1000" height="750" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1000x750/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=VO+Studio';"></figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="lede-section lede-section--with-image">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <p class="lede">Florida commercial talent operate at the intersection of SAG-AFTRA Commercials Contract framework, multi-source compensation (session fees + residuals + buyouts + holding fees), 2023 strike outcomes (AI protections + digital replica consent + streaming residual improvements), loan-out company S-corp PLLC tax efficiency, booking-variability income reality, and Florida bilingual commercial production market + Florida no-state-income-tax favorable creative practice environment. <strong>Florida commercial talent practice spans five primary categories. On-camera commercial principal as lead/featured performer in TV + streaming + theatrical commercials with session fee $711+ per day (current SAG-AFTRA Commercials Contract Class A rate, with substantial premiums for Class B + dealer commercials + extended day) + residuals on network + cable + web + foreign markets + holding fees for conflict purposes. Working commercial talent with regular bookings (3-8 commercials per year national tier) $60K-$150K; established talent with substantial bookings + recurring campaigns $150K-$350K+. Voiceover artist for commercial VO + animation + ADR (Automated Dialog Replacement) + audiobook + e-learning + corporate narration. Session fees $466+ per session (1-hour SAG-AFTRA standard) + residuals on commercial campaigns + buyouts on digital + non-broadcast use. Top-tier VO talent on recurring national campaigns (insurance + automotive + fast food + technology + pharmaceutical) $200K-$500K+ income. Home studio business common for established VO talent. Print + still photography talent with one-time fee + use period structure (typically no traditional residuals; usage-based compensation tied to media + duration + territory). Fees $1,500-$15K+ per day depending on talent tier + commercial use + territory + duration. $35K-$150K typical annual range with established bookings. Digital + social media talent for web + social + streaming + influencer-adjacent commercial work. Frequently buyout-based for streaming platforms + social media + sometimes non-union digital production. Growing category with substantial growth 2020-2026 driven by streaming + social platform commercial investment. $50K-$250K range depending on platform + reach + booking volume. Industrial + corporate + medical narration talent for internal corporate training + medical narration + e-learning + product demos + IVR (Interactive Voice Response) systems + sometimes phone systems. Frequently non-union or SAG-AFTRA Industrial agreement. $45K-$150K typical range</strong>. For mortgage qualifying, multi-source commercial talent income synthesizes under B3-3.1-01 for W-2 session fees + residuals with 24-month averaging, B3-3.2-01 for 1099 non-union work + corporate + e-learning, B3-3.4-02 for loan-out S-corp K-1. Bank Statement Non-QM + Asset-Depletion Non-QM common alternative paths. <strong>Stairway Mortgage routinely handles Florida commercial talent mortgages with multi-source synthesis + loan-out S-corp + residuals/buyouts + booking variability smoothing + bilingual market context.</strong> Skip to: <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/jumbo-loan/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline;">Jumbo</a>, <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline;">every program</a>, <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline;">calculators</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 760px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">01 &middot; Florida commercial talent mortgage qualifying at a glance</div>
        <h2>Key facts every Florida commercial talent should know about qualifying.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="key-facts-grid">
        <div class="key-fact-card"><div class="key-fact-num">Multi-source SAG-AFTRA income</div><p class="key-fact-body">Commercial talent income spans W-2 session fees + residuals + buyouts + holding fees + S-corp loan-out K-1 + 1099 non-union. Multi-source synthesis under B3-3.1-01 + B3-3.2-01 + B3-3.4-02 frameworks combining all components.</p></div>
        <div class="key-fact-card"><div class="key-fact-num">Loan-out S-corp K-1</div><p class="key-fact-body">Loan-out company S-corp PLLC under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.7-01/analyzing-partnership-returns-partnership-or-llc" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.4-02</a> with Form 1084 cash-flow analysis. Add-backs: home studio + headshots + agent + manager + attorney + business travel + audition expenses + craft expenses.</p></div>
        <div class="key-fact-card"><div class="key-fact-num">Residuals + buyouts streams</div><p class="key-fact-body">Residuals (re-use payments) + buyouts (lump-sum substituting for residuals) substantial income streams. Streaming + digital + social buyouts now substantial portion of commercial talent income. Documented through SAG-AFTRA + agency statements.</p></div>
        <div class="key-fact-card"><div class="key-fact-num">Booking variability 24-month avg</div><p class="key-fact-body">Commercial bookings produce variable booking-based income with substantial year-to-year variability + concentration around major campaign periods. 24-36 month averaging + sometimes Bank Statement Non-QM critical for stable qualifying baseline.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="professions-section section-tinted" id="commercial-roles">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">02 &middot; Florida commercial talent practice roles</div>
        <h2>The five commercial talent practice roles in Florida.</h2>
        <p>Florida commercial talent practice spans five primary categories from on-camera principal through specialized industrial narration.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="professions-grid">
        <div class="profession-card"><div class="profession-num">01</div><h3 class="profession-title">On-Camera Commercial Principal</h3><p class="profession-tag">"On-camera lead/featured performer in TV + streaming + theatrical commercials. Session fee $711+/day (SAG-AFTRA Class A) + residuals (network + cable + web + foreign) + holding fees + sometimes buyouts. Working talent (3-8 bookings/year national) $60K-$150K; established $150K-$350K+. Loan-out S-corp common."</p><ul class="profession-points"><li>SAG-AFTRA Class A $711+/day</li><li>Substantial residuals income</li><li>$60K-$350K+ range</li><li>Loan-out S-corp standard</li></ul><span class="profession-link" style="opacity: 0.65;">See on-camera principal qualifying</span></div>
        <div class="profession-card"><div class="profession-num">02</div><h3 class="profession-title">Voiceover Artist</h3><p class="profession-tag">"Voiceover for commercial VO + animation + ADR + audiobook + e-learning + corporate narration. Session fees $466+/session (1-hour SAG-AFTRA) + residuals + buyouts. Top-tier VO on recurring national campaigns (insurance, automotive, fast food, technology, pharmaceutical) $200K-$500K+. Home studio business common."</p><ul class="profession-points"><li>$466+/session SAG-AFTRA</li><li>Residuals + buyouts</li><li>$200K-$500K+ top-tier</li><li>Home studio business</li></ul><span class="profession-link" style="opacity: 0.65;">See voiceover artist qualifying</span></div>
        <div class="profession-card"><div class="profession-num">03</div><h3 class="profession-title">Print Talent</h3><p class="profession-tag">"Print + still photography commercial talent with one-time fee + use period structure. No traditional residuals; usage-based compensation tied to media + duration + territory. Fees $1,500-$15K+/day. $35K-$150K typical annual range with established bookings. SAG-AFTRA Stand-Alone Print or non-union. Frequently bilingual market opportunity."</p><ul class="profession-points"><li>One-time fee + use period</li><li>$1,500-$15K+/day</li><li>$35K-$150K typical range</li><li>SAG-AFTRA Stand-Alone Print</li></ul><span class="profession-link" style="opacity: 0.65;">See print talent qualifying</span></div>
        <div class="profession-card"><div class="profession-num">04</div><h3 class="profession-title">Digital + Social Media Talent</h3><p class="profession-tag">"Digital + social + streaming + influencer-adjacent commercial talent. Frequently buyout-based for streaming + social platforms + sometimes non-union digital production. Growing category 2020-2026 with substantial streaming + social platform commercial investment. $50K-$250K range. Sometimes hybrid SAG-AFTRA + non-union."</p><ul class="profession-points"><li>Buyout-based common</li><li>Streaming + social growth</li><li>$50K-$250K range</li><li>Sometimes hybrid SAG-AFTRA / non-union</li></ul><span class="profession-link" style="opacity: 0.65;">See digital talent qualifying</span></div>
        <div class="profession-card"><div class="profession-num">05</div><h3 class="profession-title">Industrial + Corporate + Medical Narration</h3><p class="profession-tag">"Industrial + corporate training + medical narration + e-learning + product demos + IVR systems + phone systems. Frequently non-union or SAG-AFTRA Industrial agreement. $45K-$150K typical range. Steady volume + lower per-project fees than commercial campaigns. Long-term relationships common with corporate clients."</p><ul class="profession-points"><li>Non-union / SAG-AFTRA Industrial</li><li>$45K-$150K range</li><li>Steady volume</li><li>Corporate client relationships</li></ul><span class="profession-link" style="opacity: 0.65;">See industrial narration qualifying</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" id="income-structure">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header"><div class="eyebrow">03 &middot; Commercial talent practice structure analysis</div><h2>How commercial talent practice structure affects mortgage qualifying.</h2><p>Florida commercial talent operate across five primary income structures each with distinct reporting + qualifying implications.</p></div>
      <h3>SAG-AFTRA session fees + residuals</h3>
      <p>SAG-AFTRA Commercials Contract Class A on-camera session fee $711+/day for 8-hour day + 50% premium for over-the-day work + double-time for extended hours. Voiceover session $466+/session (1-hour standard). Residuals paid for re-use: network airings ($711+ for 13-week cycle per network/region), cable runs (different formula), web (formula-based on impressions + duration), foreign use (lump-sum buyout typical). Documented through SAG-AFTRA Residuals administration + agency statements + production company payments.</p>
      <h3>Buyouts for digital + social + non-broadcast</h3>
      <p>Buyouts = lump-sum payments substituting for traditional residuals, common for digital + social + streaming + foreign + non-broadcast use. Buyout structure: session fee + lump-sum for X-year use across Y media. $5K-$500K+ depending on talent tier + use + duration + territory. Buyouts often paid to loan-out; loan-out distributes to talent through W-2 + K-1.</p>
      <h3>Holding fees + conflicts</h3>
      <p>Holding fees paid to keep commercial talent available between sessions for conflict purposes. SAG-AFTRA Commercials Contract requires holding fees for principal performers to prevent conflicting brand work (e.g., one car brand only at a time). Holding fees typically $200-$500/week depending on contract terms. Supplementary income supporting continuity narrative.</p>
      <h3>Loan-out company S-corp PLLC</h3>
      <p>Standard structure for established commercial talent. Production company / advertiser contracts loan-out (not individual talent directly). Loan-out pays W-2 wages to talent (reasonable compensation per IRS standards) + S-corp K-1 distribution from loan-out profit. Tax efficiency from S-corp election + liability shielding + business expense deduction at loan-out level (home studio + headshots + agent commission + attorney + audition expenses).</p>
      <h3>1099 non-union + corporate + e-learning</h3>
      <p>Non-union commercial work + corporate narration + e-learning + industrial production frequently paid 1099 (not W-2) to loan-out or individual talent. Schedule C / Form 1120-S documenting income + expenses. B3-3.2-01 self-employed framework with Form 1084 add-backs. Common supplementary income source for SAG-AFTRA talent combining union + non-union work.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="per-diem-section per-diem-section--bg qualifying--bg section-dark" style="background-image: url('https://images.pexels.com/photos/3771088/pexels-photo-3771088.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1800');">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="max-width: 760px;"><div class="eyebrow eyebrow-light">04 &middot; Florida commercial talent market context</div><h2 style="color: var(--paper);">Six things every Florida commercial talent should understand about market context.</h2><p style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.78);">Florida commercial talent market operates within SAG-AFTRA Commercials Contract framework + 2023 strike outcomes + streaming + digital + social commercial growth + bilingual market opportunity + booking variability + Florida no-state-income-tax favorable environment.</p></div>
      <div class="dark-grid">
        <div class="dark-card"><div class="dark-num">A</div><h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">SAG-AFTRA Commercials Contract</h3><p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">SAG-AFTRA Commercials Contract negotiated with Joint Policy Committee (JPC) representing ANA + 4As. Separate from TV/Theatrical contract governing scripted episodic + features. Governs session fees + residuals + buyouts + holding fees + working conditions + benefits for principal commercial performers. Periodic renegotiation cycle.</p></div>
        <div class="dark-card"><div class="dark-num">B</div><h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">2023 strike + AI protections</h3><p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">2023 SAG-AFTRA TV/Theatrical strike (July-November 2023) parallel to WGA strike resulted in contract improvements: AI protections (digital replica consent + compensation; AI-generated performance protections), streaming residual improvements, viewership metric transparency, minimum required staffing. Commercial talent benefit from parallel framework improvements + AI/digital replica protections.</p></div>
        <div class="dark-card"><div class="dark-num">C</div><h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Streaming + digital + social growth</h3><p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Streaming + digital + social commercial production substantial growth 2020-2026 driven by streaming platform commercial investment (Netflix + Disney+ + Amazon advertising-supported tiers) + social platform commerce + influencer marketing convergence. Buyout-based compensation common for digital. Growing category supporting commercial talent income.</p></div>
        <div class="dark-card"><div class="dark-num">D</div><h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">FL bilingual commercial market</h3><p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Miami substantial Spanish-language commercial production market (Univision + Telemundo + ViX + ViX+ targeting US Hispanic market). Bilingual commercial talent substantial career opportunity. South Florida + Orlando substantial commercial production infrastructure. Bilingual on-camera + voiceover + print talent in particular demand for US Hispanic-targeted national campaigns.</p></div>
        <div class="dark-card"><div class="dark-num">E</div><h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Booking variability reality</h3><p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Commercial bookings produce variable booking-based income with substantial year-to-year variability + concentration around major campaign periods + agency relationship dynamics. 24-36 month averaging + sometimes Bank Statement Non-QM critical. Established talent with recurring campaigns + multiple agency relationships smooth booking variability through portfolio approach.</p></div>
        <div class="dark-card"><div class="dark-num">F</div><h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">FL no-state-income-tax</h3><p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">FL no state income tax substantial commercial talent income preservation. Top-tier VO + on-camera $200K-$500K+: California (13.3%) saves $27K-$67K+; New York (10.9%) saves $22K-$55K+ annually relocating to Florida. Substantial lifetime tax preservation driving commercial talent relocations 2020-2026 with remote audition + home studio proliferation.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header"><div class="eyebrow">05 &middot; W-2 session + residuals B3-3.1-01 deep dive</div><h2>How Stairway handles W-2 session + residuals qualifying.</h2><p>SAG-AFTRA commercial talent W-2 income from session fees + residuals + buyouts + holding fees requires B3-3.1-01 framework with booking-variability smoothing.</p></div>
      <h3>Step 1 &mdash; W-2 + SAG-AFTRA documentation</h3>
      <p>2-year W-2s + 30-day paystubs covering recent sessions + SAG-AFTRA membership documentation + agency representation contracts + production company / advertiser VOEs for major recurring bookings + SAG-AFTRA Health Plan + Pension contribution statements + SAG-AFTRA Residuals statements showing prior year residuals income.</p>
      <h3>Step 2 &mdash; 24-36 month averaging on booking variability</h3>
      <p>Commercial booking income variable across years requires 24-month averaging standard, with 36-month extended averaging sometimes applied for substantial variability. Established talent with recurring national campaigns + multiple agency relationships show smoother averaging baseline. Newer talent + variable booking history may require Bank Statement Non-QM alternative with comprehensive deposit-based analysis.</p>
      <h3>Step 3 &mdash; SAG-AFTRA continuity narrative</h3>
      <p>Continuity narrative documents: SAG-AFTRA membership tenure + standing + good standing dues current, agency representation (talent agency tier + market positioning), recurring campaign tenure + relationships (auto, insurance, fast food, pharmaceutical, retail major advertiser relationships), genre + category specialization (commercial + voiceover + animation + print specialization), 2023 strike + AI protections context for digital replica consent positioning.</p>
      <h3>Step 4 &mdash; Residuals + buyouts supplementary documentation</h3>
      <p>Residuals through SAG-AFTRA Residuals administration documented through annual statements + bank deposit history. Buyouts paid directly by production / advertiser documented through bank deposit + agency statements + sometimes loan-out company books. Treated as variable supplementary income with 24-month averaging when established baseline. Established commercial talent may show $25K-$150K+ annual residuals + buyouts supporting qualifying.</p>
      <h3>Step 5 &mdash; Multi-agency + multi-source documentation</h3>
      <p>Established commercial talent frequently multi-agency representation (commercial agency + voiceover agency + sometimes print agency + sometimes commercial print specialty) + multi-source income across union + non-union + corporate work. Documentation through multiple W-2s + multiple 1099s + multiple agency statements + sometimes single loan-out aggregating all income streams. Multi-source synthesis combining all engagements.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-tinted">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header"><div class="eyebrow">06 &middot; Loan-out S-corp B3-3.4-02 deep dive</div><h2>How Stairway handles loan-out S-corp qualifying.</h2><p>Established commercial talent operating through loan-out companies require multi-entity B3-3.4-02 framework treatment.</p></div>
      <h3>Step 1 &mdash; 2-year personal + loan-out entity returns</h3>
      <p>2-year personal tax returns (Form 1040 + Schedule E for K-1 + W-2 from loan-out) + 2-year loan-out entity returns (Form 1120-S for S-corp / Form 1065 for partnership rare). Schedule K-1 documenting talent share of loan-out profit + distribution amounts. Some commercial talent operate multiple loan-out entities for different work categories (commercial vs voiceover vs corporate).</p>
      <h3>Step 2 &mdash; Loan-out ownership + agency documentation</h3>
      <p>Loan-out S-corp shareholder agreement + operating documents. Agency representation contracts (commercial + VO + sometimes print + sometimes specialty). Production company / advertiser payment history to loan-out documented through bank deposits + 1099 to loan-out + sometimes direct deposit detail from major campaigns. Substantial contract documentation supports continuity narrative.</p>
      <h3>Step 3 &mdash; Form 1084 loan-out cash-flow analysis</h3>
      <p>Form 1084 cash-flow analysis applied at loan-out level adding back: home studio (substantial for VO talent — equipment + soundproofing + microphones + audio interface + sometimes whole-room build-out), headshots + reels + demo production (annual investment for ongoing marketing), agency commission (10% standard) + manager fees (10% standard typical) + entertainment attorney fees (5% standard), audition expenses + casting workshops + acting classes + craft development, business travel for auditions + sessions + festival attendance, costuming + wardrobe + sometimes makeup for self-tape auditions.</p>
      <h3>Step 4 &mdash; W-2 + K-1 synthesis from loan-out</h3>
      <p>Commercial talent receives W-2 wages from loan-out (reasonable compensation per IRS standards typically 30-50% of total compensation) + S-corp K-1 distribution from loan-out profit (remaining 50-70%). W-2 under B3-3.1-01. K-1 under B3-3.4-02 with Form 1084 add-backs. Reasonable compensation analysis sometimes required by lender confirming S-corp wage allocation appropriate for talent + market level.</p>
      <h3>Step 5 &mdash; Bank Statement Non-QM alternative for booking variability</h3>
      <p>Loan-out income concentrated in booking-based payments with substantial year-to-year variability. Multi-year averaging (24-36 months) + Bank Statement Non-QM 12-24 months loan-out + personal bank deposits + Asset-Depletion Non-QM (liquid portfolio &divide; 360 months) common alternative paths when traditional B3-3.4-02 averaging produces volatile baseline. Senior talent with substantial accumulated savings often well-positioned for Asset-Depletion path.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header"><div class="eyebrow">07 &middot; Multi-source synthesis for commercial talent</div><h2>How Stairway combines W-2 + K-1 + 1099 + residuals/buyouts + spouse income.</h2><p>Commercial talent with multi-source income synthesize each component under appropriate framework.</p></div>
      <h3>Step 1 &mdash; W-2 session fees primary anchor</h3>
      <p>W-2 session fees from SAG-AFTRA bookings synthesized under B3-3.1-01 with 24-month averaging on booking-variability income. Primary anchor for established commercial talent with regular SAG-AFTRA work across union signatory employers.</p>
      <h3>Step 2 &mdash; Loan-out S-corp K-1 distribution</h3>
      <p>Loan-out S-corp K-1 synthesized under B3-3.4-02 with multi-entity Form 1084 analysis. Add-backs comprehensive at loan-out level (home studio + headshots + agency + manager + attorney + audition + travel + craft). Reasonable compensation analysis confirming W-2/K-1 split appropriate.</p>
      <h3>Step 3 &mdash; 1099 non-union + corporate + e-learning</h3>
      <p>1099 non-union commercial + corporate narration + e-learning + industrial work synthesized under B3-3.2-01 with Schedule C / 1120-S + Form 1084 add-backs (home studio + business travel + craft + sometimes equipment + sometimes coaching). Common supplementary income source combining union + non-union work.</p>
      <h3>Step 4 &mdash; Residuals + buyouts supplementary</h3>
      <p>Residuals through SAG-AFTRA Residuals administration + buyouts paid directly by production / advertiser documented through statements + bank deposits. Treated as variable supplementary income with 24-month averaging. Established talent with substantial booking library may show $50K-$150K+ annual residuals + buyouts supporting qualifying capacity.</p>
      <h3>Step 5 &mdash; Spouse income + final DTI</h3>
      <p>Spouse income (if applicable, often industry spouse W-2 or non-industry professional) synthesized with commercial talent multi-source income. Combined monthly qualifying calculated. Federal tax + Social Security + Medicare deductions applied (FL no state income tax substantial advantage). Net qualifying flows to DTI calculation.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

